# Built-in Rules & DSL

The coaching insights surfaced by the extension are powered by Markdown
files in [@src/core/rules/](mdc:src/core/rules/) (and user-authored files
loaded through the trust gate). Each rule pairs human-readable copy with a
constrained DSL expression that the interpreter in
[@src/core/dsl/](mdc:src/core/dsl/) evaluates against parsed sessions /
requests. The canonical authoring guide is [@docs/AUTHORING_RULES.md](mdc:docs/AUTHORING_RULES.md) —
read it before adding your first rule.

## Rule file shape

```yaml
---
id: kebab-case-id              # filename without `.md`, also the rule id
name: Human Readable Title
group: tool-mastery            # one of the PRACTICE_GROUPS keys
severity: low | medium | high
scope: requests | sessions
requiresIdeContext: true       # optional; gate on IDE harness data
version: 1
tags: [list, of, tags]
thresholds:
  minReqs: 30                  # named knobs referenced by the DSL below
  someRatio: 0.3
---

# Description
One-paragraph what & why.

# When Triggered
A sentence with `{{template}}` placeholders that get filled in at render
time (e.g. `{{count}}`, `{{pct}}`, `{{extra.someField}}`).

# How to Improve
Actionable, specific advice. Prefer imperative phrasing. Mention concrete
Cursor surfaces (Plan mode, Agent mode, `@file`, `.cursor/rules/`, etc.).

# Examples
Short bullet examples. Use mustache placeholders if data-driven.

# Detection Logic
```detect
scan: requests | sessions
match: <DSL expression returning boolean>
aggregate: count | sum | ratio | percent
check: <DSL expression — must be true to trigger>
examples: <optional template for example rows>
```
```

### Naming

- `id` is `kebab-case`, matches the filename. Do not rename a published id
  without considering downstream breakage — the id is stored in user
  trust approvals and dashboards.
- `name` is the title shown in the UI.
- `group` is one of `PRACTICE_GROUPS` in
  [@src/core/types/](mdc:src/core/types/). New groups need product
  approval — they change the dashboard tiles.

### Severity

- `high` is reserved for things with a clear cost (security, billing,
  flow destruction). Most rules are `medium` or `low`.

## DSL conventions

The DSL is **not JavaScript**. It is a constrained expression language;
the interpreter rejects anything it does not explicitly support.

- Strings are double-quoted: `"plan"`.
- Comparison: `==`, `!=`, `>`, `>=`, `<`, `<=`.
- Boolean composition: `AND`, `OR`, `NOT` (uppercase).
- Field references match the schema in
  [@src/core/dsl/schema.ts](mdc:src/core/dsl/schema.ts). If a field
  doesn't appear there, it isn't available — extend the schema first.
- Helpers like `someWhere(all, field, op, value)` and
  `lenSafe(field)` live in
  [@src/core/dsl/interpreter.ts](mdc:src/core/dsl/interpreter.ts).
- Reference `thresholds.<name>` exclusively for tunable knobs — never
  hard-code a number in `match`/`check`. This is what the Rule
  Playground tweaks.

## Cursor-only references

Because this fork is Cursor-only, write copy and examples that name
**Cursor surfaces** by their real names:

- ✅ "Switch to Plan mode in the mode picker before starting large features"
- ✅ "Use `@file` to attach the file you want edited"
- ✅ "Add hooks in `.cursor/hooks.json` to enforce checks"
- ✅ "Place reusable instructions in `.cursor/rules/<topic>.md` or `AGENTS.md`"
- ❌ Anything mentioning `/copilot`, `/claude`, `/codex`, `.github/copilot-instructions.md`,
  `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/settings.json`, `.gemini/`, Xcode, OpenCode.

## When you extend the DSL

Touching `src/core/dsl/` widens the attack surface for user-authored
rules. Every addition needs:

1. **Schema entry** in `schema.ts` (for new fields) or
   `FUNCTION_CATALOG` / `METRIC_PRIMITIVES` (for new helpers).
2. **Lexer / parser updates** in `lexer.ts` / `parser.ts` only if you're
   adding new syntax (rare). Prefer adding helper functions to the
   `FUNCTION_CATALOG` instead.
3. **Interpreter implementation** in `interpreter.ts` — keep the helper
   pure and deterministic, no I/O.
4. **Tests** for both the happy path and abuse cases (deeply nested
   inputs, regex DoS, prototype pollution attempts). See
   [@src/core/dsl/safe-regex.test.ts](mdc:src/core/dsl/safe-regex.test.ts)
   for the regex-safety pattern — always go through `safeRegex` rather
   than `new RegExp(userInput)`.
5. **Cheatsheet update** in
   [@src/webview/dsl-cheatsheet.ts](mdc:src/webview/dsl-cheatsheet.ts).

If a helper requires arbitrary computation, that is the signal to
**not** add it. The DSL is intentionally limited.

## Loader & trust

- Built-in rules in `src/core/rules/` are loaded unconditionally; they
  are part of the extension package.
- Personal rules (`~/.cursor-engineering-coach/rules/`) and project
  rules (`<workspace>/.cursor/rules/` — read by the analyzer, not the
  Cursor IDE itself) go through the trust gate. Use
  `loadAllRuleLayersAsync` and **never** parse user-provided rule
  content outside that pipeline.
- A change to an approved file revokes trust — that is intentional
  ([@src/core/rule-trust.ts](mdc:src/core/rule-trust.ts)).

## Reviewer checklist

Before opening a PR with a new built-in rule:

- [ ] File name is `kebab-case.md` and matches `id`.
- [ ] All copy is Cursor-specific (see Don'ts above).
- [ ] DSL uses `thresholds.*` — no magic numbers.
- [ ] Detection passes on `npx vitest run` (add a small fixture test if
      the rule introduces a new edge case in the interpreter).
- [ ] `npm run spellcheck` is clean (new product names go in
      [@cspell.json](mdc:cspell.json)).
- [ ] If you extended the DSL (new field in `schema.ts`, new helper in
      `FUNCTION_CATALOG`, new syntax in the lexer/parser), update the
      *DSL conventions* section above so the next rule author knows the
      surface area. Also confirm
      [@.cursor/context/architecture.md](mdc:.cursor/context/architecture.md)
      *Rules pipeline* still reads true end-to-end.
